{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"123bd745-e3ee-4601-8c5f-ac935bc5e4ff","content":"Good news — with .NET 10 SDK, `dotnet test` **natively** uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform. You **no longer need** `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`. That property was a bridge for .NET 9 and earlier SDKs; in .NET 10 it's the default behavior.\n\nYou can simply remove it:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01Ce9qFpBDGKq8WeEURLS7Mp","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-1d99ff47ef624d289172395b493ccb3a/TestProject.csproj","old_str":"    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>","new_str":"    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-1d99ff47ef624d289172395b493ccb3a/TestProject.csproj."}],"interactionId":"4dff554c-f9bd-48e0-bdf6-e06a4b36436f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is on .NET 10 SDK (10.0.100) and wants to know about MTP support. Let me check what's the current state of MTP in .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET 10, `dotnet test` has been rewritten to natively support Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). The key changes are:\n\n1. Starting with .NET 10 SDK, `dotnet test` uses MTP natively — the `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property is no longer needed.\n2. The new `dotnet test` in .NET 10 directly invokes test executables built with MTP, without going through VSTest.\n\n\n3. However, they'll still need to enable `EnableMSTestRunner` or the equivalent for their test framework to build the project as an executable that uses MTP.\n\nSo for their project, they can remove the `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property since .NET 10's `dotnet test` natively supports MTP, but they'll need to keep the framework-specific runner property enabled.","outputTokens":508,"requestId":"CFC7:335471:5C7E990:67C3805:69EC0F60"},"id":"af8112ef-54a6-4d5b-9137-7569256786ea","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:48:45.136Z","parentId":"d85766ef-96a3-4a9d-b943-623d757ee20f"}
